                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 165.102/881</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-03-16T16:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 16, 1916, 4 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 17, 1.30 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3634. Am sure if I present request made in your 2811, March 15, 12 noon, that
                    German Government will be strengthened in its belief that it can demand cotton
                    for dyestuffs. Best way to get dyestuffs out is to have bills protect the
                    American dyestuff industry introduced. Shall therefore wait for further
                    instructions. On December 13, 1915, the German Government in answer to my
                    inquiry informed me that its policy as to export dyestuffs was unchanged.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
